******
[1] Nigeria (Kano, Kebbi, Zamfara & Katsina states)
Date: Mon, 24 Apr 2006
From: Thomas Roesel <roesel@lycos.com>
Source: AllAfrica.com and Daily Trust (Abuja) [edited]
<http://allafrica.com/stories/200604240104.html>

About 40 people have been confirmed dead following an outbreak of
meningitis in Kano state. The worst-hit area is Kano city where many houses
have poor ventilation. A similar outbreak killed 6 people in Kebbi state
last week while 86 people have been treated in hospital in Zamfara state.
However, the Kano state commissioner for health, Dr Muhammad Sanda, told
Daily Trust yesterday that only 25 deaths have been officially recorded,
and that many of the deaths were recorded at the beginning of the outbreak
in early Mar 2006, but assured that the number has dropped following
immediate intervention by health officials. Dr Sanda stated that as at
yesterday, 23 Apr 2006, the number of patients at the Infectious Diseases
Hospital (IDH), Kano, was 30.
At Hasiya Bayero, about 8 children infected with the disease were still
being treated, 6 children were seen at both the adult and children's wards
of the Murtala Mohammed Specialist Hospital while at IDH, 30 people were
hospitalized. The outbreak of meningitis in Kano has become an annual event
because of poor sanitation and ventilation in many homes in the city.
In Gusau, Zamfara state, 6 people are currently receiving treatment at
various locations following the outbreak of meningitis. The most affected
areas included Tudun Wada, Sabo Gari and Filin Gunza where an undisclosed
number of people were hit by the disease.
At the Federal Medical Center, Gusau, Daily Trust gathered that victims,
mostly children were admitted and are receiving treatment. There are also
reported outbreaks of the disease in surrounding villages.
4 people were reported dead and over 1000 others affected by an outbreak of
meningitis that hit some parts of Katsina state last week. Checks conducted
by Daily Trust over the weekend revealed that children aged 10 and 12
years, mostly beggars, are the worst affected.
A report obtained exclusively by Daily Trust from Katsina General Hospital,
shows that in the pediatric ward alone, a total of 78 children were
affected from 1 to 19 Apr 2006, of whom 46 were discharged. The record
further indicated that most of the cases came from Tudun Yanlifidda, Kofar
Marusa and Kofar Kaura areas of Katsina metropolis and are mostly beggars
sleeping in a congested environment with about 50 to 60 children.
[byline: Musa Umar Kazaure, Salisu Zakari Maradun & Lawal Ibrahim]
--
Thomas Roesel, MD
<roesel@lycos.com>
[ProMED-mail thanks Dr Roesel for his contribution. A map of Nigeria can be
found at: <http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/nigeria.pdf>.
The states mentioned are all in the north part of the country. - Mod.LL]
