[2] Guinea (Kankan)
Date: Sun, 23 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail promed@promedmail.org
Source: News24.com [edited]
<http://www.news24.com/News24/Africa/News/0,,2-11-1447_1921368,00.html>

A meningitis epidemic in Eastern Guinea has hit at least 168 people and
killed 17 since the beginning of Apr 2006, the Swiss branch of Medecins
sans Frontieres (MSF) said on Sun, 23 Apr 2006.
According to Gerard Bedock, head of MSF-Switzerland's mission in Guinea,
the disease first appeared in the far eastern provincial capital, Mandiana,
between 4 and 6 Apr 2006, before spreading to other areas, including
Faralako, Koundian, Morodou, and Kinieran near the Malian border.
"At least 168 cases have been recorded, 17 of these being fatal", Bedock
said, "that means the mortality rate is 10 per cent."
Bedock also announced that a crisis committee was set up this weekend to
start a campaign of vaccination in the region, for which the health
ministry, WHO and UNICEF had brought 200 000 doses of the vaccine to the
area, along with other medicines.
Guinea is in the so-called "meningitis belt" that runs from the Southern
Sahara in Senegal to Ethiopia, and whose total population is estimated at
300 million people. The disease usually breaks out during the dry season,
which starts in Dec-Jan when the warm, dry Harmattan wind begins to blow,
spreading meningitis germs.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[Mandiana's location in eastern Guinea can be seen at
<http://www.un.org/Depts/Cartographic/map/profile/guinea.pdf> in the Kankan
district. The Harmattan is a dry and dusty wind blowing south west and west
off the Sahara into the Gulf of Guinea between Nov and Mar. It is
considered a natural hazard.
On its passage over the desert it picks up fine dust particles (between 0.5
and 10 micrometers). When the Harmattan blows hard, it can push dust and
sand all the way to South America. In some countries in West Africa, the
heavy amount of dust in the air can severely limit visibility and block the
sun for several days, comparable to a heavy fog. The effect caused by the
dust and sand stirred by these winds is known as the Harmattan Haze, and
costs airlines millions in cancelled and diverted flights each year. In
Niger, people say that men and animals become increasingly irritable when
this wind has been blowing for a while, giving it a bad reputation. But the
cool wind brings relief from the oppressive heat, which is why the
Harmattan has earned the nickname "The Doctor" (source:
<http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harmattan> - Mod.LL]
******
[3] Niger, Burkina Faso
Date: Wed, 12 Apr 2006
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: News24.com [edited]
<http://www.news24.com/News24/Africa/News/0,,2-11-1447_1915170,00.html>

An outbreak of meningitis in Niger has killed 109 people since the start of
2006 and infected 1550 others, more than double the number of deaths
recorded by the UN a month ago, say officials.
The UN Office for the Co-ordination of Humanitarian Affairs (OCHA) said
last week that 802 people had been infected by the disease in Niger between
1 Jan and 10 Mar 2006, of whom 52 had died.
The Niger government's national health information system (SNIS) said the
outbreak this year was significantly worse than 2005, when 550 people were
infected and 76 of them died.
The OCHA said that in neighboring Burkina Faso, meningitis had infected
6110 people and killed 616 of them by 18 Mar 2006, a death rate per
infection of 10.8 per cent.
Niger and Burkina Faso, 2 of the world's poorest countries, are situated in
the Africa's meningitis belt, which stretched from Senegal in the west to
Ethiopia in the east and had a population of about 300 million.
--
